    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-08T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-08T11:00:00-05:00" n="202"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d202">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.002/1–247</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minutes of a Meeting of the Secretaries of State, War, and
                        Navy, Washington, January 8, 1947, 11 a.m</hi>.</head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                        ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1947-01-08T11:00:00-05:00">January 8, 1947, 11 a.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of various subjects.]</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Disarmament in</hi> UN</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Forrestal</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d202fn1">James Forrestal, Secretary of the Navy; appointed
                        first Secretary of Defense, July 26, 1947.</note> asked whether in Mr.
                    Byrnes’ opinion Senator Austin would hold the position that an atomic agreement
                    must come first in connection with the disarmament discussions. <hi
                        rend="smallcaps">Mr. Byrnes</hi> replied that he was confident Senator
                    Austin would maintain this position. Mr. <hi rend="smallcaps">Forrestal</hi>
                    asked whether the British and French would support us. <hi rend="smallcaps">The
                        Secretary</hi> said that he thought the British would support us but he was
                    less definite about the position of the French. <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr.
                        Patterson</hi> pointed out that the UN Assembly resolution of last month
                    stipulated that agreement should first be won on atomic energy and other weapons
                    of mass destruction. He said that he felt that it was important that everybody
                    understand that the reference to other weapons of mass destruction stemmed from
                    the Tripartite Declaration of late 1945 issued by President Truman, Prime
                    Minister Attlee and Prime Minister King<note n="2" xml:id="d202fn2">Department
                        of State Treaties and Other International Acts Series (TIAS) No. 1504, or 60
                        Stat. (pt. 2) 1479.</note> and that this reference clearly meant <hi
                        rend="italic">new</hi> means of mass destruction. He said that as a matter
                    of fact the only means of mass destruction discussed at the meeting which lead
                    to the statement dealt with biological warfare. In any event, he said that it
                    should be clearly understood that it relates to new weapons or means of mass
                    destruction. He said the Russians would undoubtedly try to <pb facs="0376"
                        n="346" xml:id="pg_346"/> stretch this to mean major weapons such as bombers
                    and perhaps even 16” guns.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion of another subject.]</p>
            </div>
